parse_iso() forces tzinfo=UTC via .replace(tzinfo=timezone.utc) even if the timestamp string includes an explicit offset (e.g., +01:00). That would silently misinterpret non-UTC timestamps. Consider: parse with fromisoformat; if the result is offset-aware, convert with .astimezone(timezone.utc); if it’s naive, then attach UTC.
```suggestion
    dt = datetime.fromisoformat(ts_trimmed)
    # If the parsed datetime is naive, assume it is already in UTC.
    # If it is offset-aware, convert it to UTC while preserving the instant.
    if dt.tzinfo is None:
        return dt.replace(tzinfo=timezone.utc)
    return dt.astimezone(timezone.utc)
```
